Alien analysis & workshop notes

Ian Handel

11/04/2018

Introduction

Heres the tidied up notes from the alien-analysis session. This document was made by knitting an RMarkdown file which loads in the alien data from an Excel workbook (in the same folder), cleans it and then analyses it. The RMarkdown file is very similar to the one you will have made in the workshop. Weve added some lines to the header to make a table of contents and to change the colour scheme. Theres also more text added to explain whats going on. Finally weve added some further code to demonstrate more features of R including data management, plotting and some basic statistics. When youre reading through these notes you can also look at the alien_analysis_20180404.Rmd RMarkdown file to see the code that made it.

Well include web links to Hadley Wickham and Garrett Grolemunds excellent R for Data Science book R4DS and other sources with more detail where relevant.

R code is shown in these notes in boxes with a light grey background. R output is shown in boxes with a white background with ## at the left hand side of each line.

Get data in

As the data is stored in Excel we use the read_excel() function from the readxl package to import it. This function is given the filename, the sheet name or number (sheet=) and optionally the codes for missing data (na=). Our code reads the first sheet from alien_analysis_20180404.Rmd into a new R object called alien. Remember that were not changing the Excel sheet - just reading it into R and putting it into an object were calling alien.

alien <- read_excel("aliendata_20180404.xlsx", sheet = 1, na = "-999")

Once the data is in R we can look at the top of it by clicking on its name in the environment tab/panel (top right part of the RSTudio window) or by typing View(alien) into the console (note that View" has a capital V). Once weve had a look we can start cleaning and tidying it ready for analysis.

Data tidy and clean

Fill missing regions

First thing to do is to fill down the missing cells in the region column. The following R code takes the alien object, pipes it into the fill function/verb and fills the region column. The result is put back into the alien object with <-. Remember, this changes the alien object in R but doesnt alter the spreadsheet. This is important. It means our original data is untouched and is always available if we change out minds about our tidying!

If you want to look at what the code is doing one step at a time you can run each code chunk in the alien_analysis_20180404.Rmd file at a time (using the little green arrow at its right hand side) and keep looking back at the alien data to see it change.

alien <- alien %>%
  fill(region)

Remove names

Next well remove the alien names - its personal data that we dont need and would rather not have on our screens (aliens have rights too!). The select() verb/function lets us do this. If we give it column names either one at a time or in a range with : between them it will keep those columns. If we put a - infront of one or more column names it will remove them. See R4DS for more detailed instructions on using select().

alien <- alien %>%
  select(-name)

Improve the subject iD format

Teh subject ID is currebtly a number. Wwe prefer IDs to be formatted so thay are unambiguously an ID and to be the same number of charcters long. We use a new verb/function here mutate. You pipe a data frame into mutate and give it the name of the column you want to create then = and then an expression (recispe) for the column. If you create an existing column it effectively overwirites it. So first off we overwrite subject using the str_pad function (this function is in the stringr)

Tidy ID column

alien <- alien %>%
  mutate(subject = str_pad(subject, width = 3, side = "left", pad = "0")) %>% 
  mutate(subject = str_c("A", subject))

Separate type column

alien <- alien %>%
  separate(type, into = c("sex", "colour"), sep = "_")

Take the first letter of sex column and correct colour column

library(stringr)
alien <- alien %>%
  mutate(sex = str_sub(sex, start = 1, end = 1)) %>%
  mutate(colour = str_to_lower(colour))

Rename columns

alien <- alien %>%
  rename(glucose = "glucose - mg/L",
         iq = "IQ - ref to human 100 scale!")

Plotting!!!!

Scatterplot

ggplot(data = alien, aes(x = age, y = weight, colour = sex)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~region)

Boxplot

ggplot(alien, aes(x= region, y = glucose, colour = sex)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  geom_jitter(width=0.2, size=0.5) + 
  theme_bw()

Histogram

ggplot(alien, aes(x = glucose, fill = sex)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 50) + 
  facet_wrap(~sex, ncol = 1)

Glucose level by health state

ggplot(alien, aes(x = health, y = glucose)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x = "Health status",
       y = "Glucose (mg/L)",
       title = "Alien blood glucose by health state",
       subtitle = "March 2060 data")

ggplot(alien, aes(x = age, y = iron, colour = sex)) +
  geom_point(shape = 1) +

  theme_bw() +
